bzdiff

The bzdiff command in Linux is used to compare and display the differences between two bzip2 compressed files. It is a command-line tool that can be used to compare the contents of compressed files.

Here are some commonly used bzdiff commands:

bzdiff file1.bz2 file2.bz2: This command compares the contents of the two specified compressed files file1.bz2 and file2.bz2 and displays the differences between them.

bzdiff -c file1.bz2 file2.bz2: This command compares the contents of the two specified compressed files file1.bz2 and file2.bz2 and displays the differences between them in a context format.

bzdiff -u file1.bz2 file2.bz2: This command compares the contents of the two specified compressed files file1.bz2 and file2.bz2 and displays the differences between them in a unified format.

bzdiff --help: This command displays the help message for bzdiff, which includes a list of available options and usage examples.

Note that bzdiff is a command-line tool that is used to compare the contents of two compressed files. It is useful for verifying that a compressed file has not been corrupted during transmission or storage, or for identifying changes between two different versions of the same file.





